{"name":"Enlightened Gun Fu!","type":"edge","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/edge.svg","data":{"description":"Integrated training has honed this warrior’s reflexes to the point that pistols are an extension of her body. She may fire pistols when using Combat Edges such as First Strike, Frenzy, and Sweep.","notes":"Interface Zero 3.0 Players Guide page 43","additionalStats":[],"isArcaneBackground":false,"requirements":{"value":"Seasoned, Gun Fu!, Fighting d10+, Shooting d10+"}},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.interface-zero-30.g1vrlnIgwUY78QkG"},"cf":{"id":"temp_blbm6prf7","path":"Interface Zero 3.0","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"Rf257t4pHeUMuNkM"}
{"name":"Cardassian Memory Training","type":"edge","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/edge.svg","data":{"description":"It's a misconception that Cardassians naturally have a photographic memory; in fact, it results from a school system that used classified techniques to discipline its students' minds. Since the government's collapse, these techniques have become public.</p><p>Once per session, you may \"remember\" everything that could reasonably be known about an NPC, including gossip, prior chance encounters, and classified records you have access to. This may allow you to befriend or pressure the person more easily.","notes":"Star Trek page 7","additionalStats":[],"isArcaneBackground":false,"requirements":{"value":"Novice; Smarts d6"}},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.star-trek.xTmIaQSfp9xrRHv2"},"cf":{"id":"temp_5vc1mrusgz","path":"Star Trek","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"S50ZSwnr2hyV3xJ7"}
{"name":"Augmented Master","type":"edge","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/edge.svg","data":{"description":"The cybermonk has learned how to use her cyberlimb for both offensive and defensive purposes, granting an additional Chi point each combat encounter.","notes":"Interface Zero 3.0 Players Guide page 45","additionalStats":[],"isArcaneBackground":false,"requirements":{"value":"Veteran, Chi, Cybermonk"}},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.interface-zero-30.UdMtohuD2huNO6N0"},"cf":{"id":"temp_blbm6prf7","path":"Interface Zero 3.0","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"SdcidwLEEKDGdP9X"}
{"name":"Augmented Warrior","type":"edge","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/edge.svg","data":{"description":"The character has learned how to use his cyberlimb for both offensive and defensive purposes. Augmented warriors increase their Parry by 1 and roll Str+d4 when hitting with their cyberlimbs. If they already have a damage die from the Brawler Edge, Martial Artist Edge, etc., increase the damage by one die type.","notes":"Interface Zero 3.0 Players Guide page 43","additionalStats":[],"isArcaneBackground":false,"requirements":{"value":"Novice, Martial Artist, Agility d8+, Cyberlimb"}},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.interface-zero-30.rhffXXQjz771ECfe"},"cf":{"id":"temp_blbm6prf7","path":"Interface Zero 3.0","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"Sfpbh47PW8be5Gtc"}
{"name":"Rocket Jock","type":"edge","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/edge.svg","data":{"description":"The pilot can fire one weapon system per action without incurring a multi-action penalty while Piloting or Driving a vehicle, aircraft, or starship.","notes":"Science Fiction Companion page 12","additionalStats":[],"isArcaneBackground":false,"requirements":{"value":"Novice, Piloting d8, Shooting d6"}},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.science-fiction-companion.Cv2D3ggLPI5VAAel"},"cf":{"id":"temp_s841qkj1579","path":"Science Fiction Companion","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"T4TdEuG46Jo7vxqN"}
{"name":"Veteran O’ The Way Out West","type":"edge","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/edge.svg","data":{"description":"Your spacer has fought pirates in the Belt, dodged twisters in Tornado Alley, and scrapped with anouks in the Cold. There’s little in Faraway she hasn’t faced down and lived to tell about. Your character starts at Seasoned Rank, which means she has four Advances to spend immediately after character creation.</p><p>That experience doesn’t come free,however. The Faraway system has left its mark. If you take this Edge, draw a single card from the Action Deck and show it to the Marshal. There’s a table on page 105 that tells her what your character faced in the past and what effect it had on her. Here’s a free bit of advice, though—the results can be pretty harsh, anything from a lost limb to insanity or worse!","notes":"Deadlands Lost Colony page 37","additionalStats":[],"isArcaneBackground":false,"requirements":{"value":"Wild Card, Novice, Occult d6+"}},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.deadlands-lost-colony.BmyGqICkKSThLPkF"},"cf":{"id":"temp_ozkdrtlws","path":"Deadlands: Lost Colony","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"TSy26XXXUwHDDLVL"}
{"name":"Transporter Chief","type":"edge","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/edge.svg","data":{"description":"What piece of technology is more subtle and more versatile than the transporter? Performing complex tasks with the transporter is normally penalized, e.g...</p><p>• Boarding an enemy ship during combat: –2</p><p>• Beaming \"site-to-site\": –2</p><p>• Storing someone long-term in the computer: –4</p><p>• Beaming the knife out of an enemy's hand: –4</p><p>• Duplicating a person: –6</p><p>• Opening a door to the Mirror Universe: –6</p><p>With this edge, you are a proven transporter expert. You ignore up to 4 penalties when performing complex transporter actions.","notes":"Star Trek page 8","additionalStats":[],"isArcaneBackground":false,"requirements":{"value":"Veteran; Knowledge (Starship Operations) d10; Knowledge (Astronomy) d6; Knowledge (Computers) d6."}},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.star-trek.3aeb2K9r7xAfAs4P"},"cf":{"id":"temp_5vc1mrusgz","path":"Star Trek","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"TgIYvNx8Qsa5MkA0"}
{"name":"Tannis Bond","type":"edge","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/edge.svg","data":{"description":"Banshee imbues certain of her children with her phenomenal energy. Those so chosen add +2 to the damage total of any attack made with a tannis weapon, and the bonus of any armor made from tannis (such as aknouk breastplates, see page 45), is treated as additional Toughness rather than Armor (so it ignores the AP value of incoming attacks).</p><p>Both bonuses count as “magical.”","notes":"Deadlands Lost Colony page 39","additionalStats":[],"isArcaneBackground":false,"requirements":{"value":"Seasoned, Anouk or Banshee Born or Guardian, Spirit d6+"}},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.deadlands-lost-colony.TF3HBPjry9gJgDO3"},"cf":{"id":"temp_ozkdrtlws","path":"Deadlands: Lost Colony","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"TzlWRmMv0bcplQuP"}
{"name":"Atmospheric Acclimation","type":"edge","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/edge.svg","data":{"description":"Travelers who have spent substantial time in Thin or Dense Atmosphere (see page 26) can learn breathing techniques to negate its ill effects. This Edge may be taken twice, once for each kind of atmosphere. Doing so allows the character to operate normally in that environment—he doesn’t have to make Vigor rolls.","notes":"Science Fiction Companion page 12","additionalStats":[],"isArcaneBackground":false,"requirements":{"value":"Novice"}},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.science-fiction-companion.dSRwddTELCuYdGes"},"cf":{"id":"temp_s841qkj1579","path":"Science Fiction Companion","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"U2uFoVungHzuEYLX"}
{"_id":"UK5vC1Kbc9NroJxt","name":"Powerful Machines","type":"edge","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/edge.svg","data":{"description":"The nanomachines have become more powerful in operation and allow the mage to be have double the range for swarm traps. ","notes":"Nano-Mage Arcane Background, page 3","additionalStats":[],"isArcaneBackground":false,"requirements":{"value":"Nano-Mage, Seasoned, Master d8"}},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.nano-mage.cEF3Eip7GrndKZlQ"},"cf":{"id":"temp_im5ud42srva","color":"#000000"}}}
{"name":"Harrowed","type":"edge","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/edge.svg","data":{"description":"Some spacers are just too tough to lie down and stay dead when their time comes. The price they pay is an eternal battle for their own souls with demonic “manitous.”In return, the treacherous creatures grant their host’s unlife and incredible powers.</p><p>Harrowed aren’t common anywhere, particularly the Faraway system, but a few have risen from Banshee’s soil over the years.</p><p>You can read up on the Harrowed in No Man’s Land (page 76). The Edge may only be selected at character creation, for obvious reasons. You can’t take it later...at least not on purpose.","notes":"Deadlands Lost Colony page 39","additionalStats":[],"isArcaneBackground":false,"requirements":{"value":"Wild Card, Novice, Spirit d6+"}},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.deadlands-lost-colony.jIg03rgdbcwW59pm"},"cf":{"id":"temp_ozkdrtlws","path":"Deadlands: Lost Colony","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"W1zpW8ECul6JTH9U"}
{"name":"Scientific Insight","type":"edge","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/edge.svg","data":{"description":"You can spend a bennie to ask the GM for special insight into the current problem or situation. This can be the answer to a yes-no question, or some simple facts—GM's discretion—but it should be relevant and useful information. You should come up with some scientific basis for your new burst of insight.","notes":"Star Trek page 8","additionalStats":[],"isArcaneBackground":false,"requirements":{"value":"Scholar applied to any two purely scientific disciplines (e.g., Computers, Astronomy, Biology, but not Jazz or Tactics)."}},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.star-trek.HAanr05Rd1J3HUUY"},"cf":{"id":"temp_5vc1mrusgz","path":"Star Trek","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"Wu1MBiRMqCU26aFf"}
{"name":"Picard Maneuver","type":"edge","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/edge.svg","data":{"description":"A clever (and daring) pilot may ‘pump’ the warp engines for a split-second in order to confuse her foes by seeming to appear in two places at once.</p><p>Roll Piloting, opposed by the enemy commander's Smarts. With a success, the enemy vessel receives 1 fewer initiative cards on the next round. With a raise, the enemy commander is also Shaken. With a failure, your ship flounders in space, receiving 1 fewer initiative cards on the next round.","notes":"Star Trek page 8","additionalStats":[],"isArcaneBackground":false,"requirements":{"value":"Seasoned; Ace; Knowledge (Tactics) d6"}},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.star-trek.kxmE8act6wLiEYGf"},"cf":{"id":"temp_5vc1mrusgz","path":"Star Trek","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"XvCWv8smwQnF3K1J"}
{"name":"Tale-teller","type":"edge","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/edge.svg","data":{"description":"A good storyteller not only entertains, he gives hope and comfort as well. Colonists and spacers in the Way Out West can use all the hope and comfort they can find. We don’t want to say too much, but good tale- tellers are critical to saving the world.</p><p>What? The world needs saving? You bet it does. Spreading the tales of your posse’s derring-do is far more important in the grand scheme of things than the ability to fire a gun or ride a chanouk. So if you do something amazing, bucko, tell people about it!</p><p>The Marshal has the skinny on all this (see page 101), but the basics are that if you ever make a Persuasion roll to lower the local Fear Level, you add +2 to your total.</p><p>When a Tale-Teller successfully lowers the local Fear Level, he and anyone who Supports the storytelling attempt automatically earn a Conviction token (see Savage Worlds). Talk to the Marshal about this, amigo. We’ve already told you more than we should.","notes":"Deadlands Lost Colony page 38","additionalStats":[],"isArcaneBackground":false,"requirements":{"value":"Novice, Persuasion d8+"}},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.deadlands-lost-colony.YCssDnUeJo2ZN9ka"},"cf":{"id":"temp_ozkdrtlws","path":"Deadlands: Lost Colony","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"YEjNendhpGF2e5Mu"}
{"name":"Cage Breaker","type":"edge","img":"systems/swade/assets/icons/edge.svg","data":{"description":"You are practiced in the art of War Driving, the art of hacking network signals from a distance. You can hack a network without needing to be inside the building so long as the building is within range of your Personal Area Network. Additionally, you ignore 2 penalties to Hacking rolls (or get a +1 to Hacking rolls if there are no penalties) during Dramatic Tasks when hacking a network.</p><p>Note: This Edge does not work with a Hacking Rig unless the Hacking Rig has a WIFI module installed. See page 130 for more information.","notes":"Interface Zero 3.0 Players Guide page 43","additionalStats":[],"isArcaneBackground":false,"requirements":{"value":"Heroic, Hacking d12, Hacker"}},"effects":[],"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"UeH4lLk57wAOn2HV":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.world.interface-zero-30.q6b16zHQT333aYw9"},"cf":{"id":"temp_blbm6prf7","path":"Interface Zero 3.0","color":"#000000"}},"_id":"YYOqJhVEvl3WzhZt"}
